He scored seven goals in 11 appearances in [[2006_FIFA_World_Cup_qualification_(UEFA)|qualifying]] for the [[2006_FIFA_World_Cup|2006 FIFA World Cup]],<ref name="Fernando Torres FIFA">{{cite web|title=Fernando Torres|url=http://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/statisticsandrecords/players/player=183864/index.html|publisher=FIFA|accessdate=2011-05-18}}</ref> making him Spain's top scorer for qualification, including a vital two goals against [[Belgium_national_football_team|Belgium]] and his first international hat-trick against [[San_Marino_national_football_team|San Marino]].<ref name="Torres"/> At his first ever appearance in a [[FIFA_World_Cup|FIFA World Cup]] finals at the 2006 FIFA World Cup in Germany, Torres scored the final goal in a 4–0 victory over [[Ukraine_national_football_team|Ukraine]] with a volley.<ref name="Spain 4-0 Ukraine">{{Cite news|url=http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4852902.stm |title=Spain 4–0 Ukraine|publisher=BBC Sport|date=2006-06-14|accessdate=2011-05-18}}</ref> In the second group match, Torres scored twice against [[Tunisia_national_football_team|Tunisia]], first in the 76th minute to take Spain 2–1 into the lead, and then again from a [[penalty_kick|penalty kick]] in the 90th.<ref name="Spain - Tunisia">{{cite web|title=Spain – Tunisia|url=http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/results/matches/match=97410031/report.html|publisher=FIFA|accessdate=2011-05-18|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017150726/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/results/matches/match=97410031/report.html|archivedate=2013-10-17|dead-url=no}}</ref> With three goals, he finished the tournament as Spain's top scorer along with fellow striker [[David_Villa|David Villa]].<ref name="Top goals">{{cite web|url=http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/statistics/players/topgoals.html|title=Top goals|publisher=FIFA|accessdate=2008-06-11|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213021026/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/statistics/players/topgoals.html|archivedate=2013-12-13|dead-url=no}}</ref>

He was called up for Spain's [[UEFA_Euro_2008|UEFA Euro 2008]] squad,<ref name="Raul left out of Spain Euro squad">{{Cite news|url=http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/euro_2008/spain/7406263.stm |title=Raul left out of Spain Euro squad|publisher=BBC Sport|date=2008-05-17|accessdate=2011-05-18}}</ref> where he set up Villa to score Spain's first goal of the tournament in the first game in the group stage against [[Russia_national_football_team|Russia]].<ref name="Quicksilver Villa lights up the Alps">{{Cite news|first=Barney|last=Ronay|title=Quicksilver Villa lights up the Alps|url=http://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2008/jun/10/quicksilvervillalightsupth|newspaper=The Guardian|location=London|date=2008-06-10|accessdate=2014-08-05}}</ref> Torres came under criticism for apparently refusing to shake the hand of Spanish manager, [[Luis_Aragonés|Luis Aragonés]], after being substituted.<ref name="Torres plays up respect for Aragones">{{cite news|first=Daniel|last=Taylor|url=http://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/jun/14/euro2008.euro2008groupd  |title= Torres plays up respect for Aragones|newspaper=The Guardian| location=London|date=2008-06-14|accessdate=2014-08-05}}</ref> He subsequently denied being angry with the coaching, saying that he was actually "irritated with himself".<ref name="Torres plays up respect for Aragones"/> He scored his first goal of the tournament in Spain's next game, a 2–1 win over [[Sweden_national_football_team|Sweden]].<ref name="Sweden 1-2 Spain">{{Cite news|first=Chris|last=Bevan|url=http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/euro_2008/7363455.stm |title= Sweden 1–2 Spain|publisher=BBC Sport|date=2008-06-14|accessdate=2011-05-18}}</ref> Torres scored the winner and was named the [[man_of_the_match|man of the match]] in the [[UEFA_Euro_2008_Final|final]] against [[Germany_national_football_team|Germany]] in a 1–0 victory.<ref name="Germany 0-1 Spain">{{Cite news|first=Phil|last=McNulty|url=http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/euro_2008/7363545.stm |title= Germany 0–1 Spain|publisher=BBC Sport|date=2008-06-29|accessdate=2011-05-18}}</ref><ref name="Euro 2008: Man of the match, 29 June">{{Cite news|first=Martin|last=Rogers|title=Euro 2008: Man of the match, June 29|url=http://sports.yahoo.com/soccer/blog/dirty-tackle/post/Euro-2008-Man-of-the-match-June-29?urn=sow-90891|publisher=Yahoo! Sports|date=2008-06-29|accessdate=2011-05-18|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025222933/http://sports.yahoo.com/soccer/blog/dirty-tackle/post/Euro-2008-Man-of-the-match-June-29?urn=sow-90891|archivedate=2012-10-25|dead-url=no}}</ref> He said "It's just a dream come true. This is my first title and I hope it's the first of many. Victory in a Euro, it is almost as big as a World Cup. We are used to watching finals on television, but today we were here and we won. My job is to score goals. I want to win more titles and be the most important player in Europe and the world."<ref name="Spain view">{{Cite news|url=http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/euro_2008/spain/7371390.stm |title= Spain view|publisher=BBC Sport|date=2008-06-30|accessdate=2011-05-18}}</ref> He was later named as a striker along with his striking partner Villa in the Team of the Tournament.<ref name="Team of the Tournament">{{Cite news| title = Team of the Tournament| url = http://www.uefa.com/MultimediaFiles/Download/PressRelease/uefa/UEFAMedia/72/93/81/729381_DOWNLOAD.pdf| format = PDF| publisher = UEFA| date = 2008-06-30| accessdate = 2010-06-20}}</ref>

