Having undergone knee surgery on 18 April 2010, and missed the end of the Premier League season, Torres' rehabilitation and fitness was closely monitored by Spain manager [[Vicente_del_Bosque|Vicente del Bosque]].<ref name="Liverpool's Fernando Torres out for rest of season"/> Although still out injured, Torres was selected for Spain's 2010 FIFA World Cup squad in May.<ref name="Spain omit Marcos Senna from 2010 World Cup squad">{{Cite news| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2010/8695232.stm| title = Spain omit Marcos Senna from 2010 World Cup squad| publisher = BBC Sport| date = 2010-05-20| accessdate = 2011-05-18}}</ref> On 8 June, Torres made his first appearance on the field in exactly two months, coming on as a substitute on 66 minutes against [[Poland_national_football_team|Poland]] in a pre-World Cup friendly.<ref name="Spain omit Marcos Senna from 2010 World Cup squad">{{Cite news| title = World Cup 2010 – Torres helps Spain rout Poland| url = http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/09062010/58/world-cup-2010-torres-helps-spain-rout-poland.html| publisher = Yahoo! UK & Ireland Eurosport| date = 2010-06-28| accessdate = 2010-11-14}}</ref>

